<div id="pf5d" class="pf w2 h0" data-page-no="5d"><div class="pc pc5d w2 h0"><div class="t m6bc xd h1b y443 ff5 fs14 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">TUESDAY </div><div class="t m6bd x1a h3d y218 ff2 fs14 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">March 9 </div><div class="t m6be x0 h25 y655 ff5 fs18 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Seeds of the Spirit </div><div class="t m19 xb4 h2 y655 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(John 1:32, 33; 3:5-8; 4:23, 24; </div><div class="t m160 x0 h2 y3e2 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">6:63; 7:37-39). </div><div class="t m540 x5b h2 y37 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">There are eleven passages in the Gospel of John that refer either </div><div class="t m453 x0 h2 y84a ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">directly or indirectly to the nature and work of the Holy Spirit. Five of </div><div class="t m376 x0 h2 y84b ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">these passages are located in the narrative section of the first half of </div><div class="t m250 x0 h2 y84c ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">the book. These passages mention the Spirit only in passing. It is as </div><div class="t m3ea x0 h2 y39 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">though John were using these passages to plant seeds in the reader&apos;s </div><div class="t m341 x0 h2 y84d ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">mind that would sprout only in the fertile soil of Jesus&apos; farewell </div><div class="t m5f1 x0 h2 y3a ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">speech </div><div class="t m16b x13 h2 y3a ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(John 13-16). </div><div class="t m1d9 x8e h38 y84e ff5 fs21 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">What </div><div class="t m113 x5b h7 y3b ff5 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> can we learn about the </div><div class="t m3e2 x12 h2 y356 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">work of the Spirit from John 1:32, 33; </div><div class="t m459 x0 h7 y84f ff5 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">3:5-8; 4:23, 24; and 7:37-39? </div><div class="t m371 x5b h2 y203 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Although the Spirit makes several appearances in the first half of </div><div class="t m365 x0 h2 y2e7 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">this Gospel, there is little information about Him. The Spirit makes it </div><div class="t m683 xbd h2 y2e8 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">possible for the Baptist to identify Jesus at the Jordan </div><div class="t m3bf xd6 h2 y77c ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(John 1:32, 33). </div><div class="t m17c xbd h2 y2e9 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">He is an essential part of human participation in the kingdom of God </div><div class="t m2a1 xbd h2 y3e8 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(John 3:5, 6). </div><div class="t m6bf x52 h2 y3e8 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Although His work cannot be controlled by human </div><div class="t m206 xbd h2 y850 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">beings, His effect on people can be seen </div><div class="t m6c0 xc1 h2 y3e9 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(vs. 8). </div><div class="t m1b7 xb h2 y3e9 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Worship is no longer </div><div class="t m27d xbd h2 y2eb ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">tied down to specific locations or temples, nor is it limited to any par-</div><div class="t m305 xbd h2 y661 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">ticular people </div><div class="t m18f x7d h2 y2ec ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(John 4:23, 24). </div><div class="t m4db x97 h2 y2ec ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">He is available in every place and to </div><div class="t m151 xbd h2 y3ea ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">anyone of any background through the words of Jesus </div><div class="t m234 x31 h2 y4bb ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(John 6:63). </div><div class="t m26a x6a h2 y20a ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The exact nature of the Spirit&apos;s work would become manifest only </div><div class="t m36a xbd h2 y7c7 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">in the context of the Cross </div><div class="t m59 x8b h2 y3ec ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(John 7:39). </div><div class="t m17f xc1 h2 y77d ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">So, John 7:37-39 is a transi-</div><div class="t m65b xbd h2 y3ed ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">tional passage, preparing the reader for the clearer, more-detailed </div><div class="t m506 x67 h2 y3ee ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">information about the Spirit&apos;s work that comes in the farewell dis-</div><div class="t m367 xbd h2 y3ef ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">course of John 13-16. John 20:22 (&quot;And . . . he breathed on them and </div><div class="t m276 xbd h2 y7c9 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">said, &apos;Receive the Holy Spirit&apos; &quot; </div><div class="t m604 xbb h2 y7c9 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">[NIVJ) </div><div class="t m202 x8 h2 y3f0 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">shows that the promise of </div><div class="t m5e6 x67 h2 y3f1 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">John 7:39 in fact began to be fulfilled right after Jesus&apos; &quot;glorifi-</div><div class="t m377 x67 h2 y54 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">cation&quot; on the cross. </div><div class="t m4bd x6a h2 y6be ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">In John 14-16, the title given to the Spirit is a Greek noun that can </div><div class="t m2ec x67 h2 y851 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">be translated as &quot;Comforter&quot; or &quot;Counselor.&quot; The root meaning of </div><div class="t m4c4 x67 h2 y39f ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">paraclete is </div><div class="t m372 x63 h2 y531 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">a person who is called alongside to help someone. So the </div><div class="t m610 x67 h2 y852 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">word can be used in the legal sense of a defense attorney at a trial who </div><div class="t m1b8 x67 h2 y853 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">appeals in behalf of another or as one who comes to comfort some-</div><div class="t m40c x67 h2 y854 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">one who is overwhelmed with grief at a time of loss. Both meanings </div><div class="t m642 x67 h2 y6 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">fit well into the context of John 14-16. </div><div class="t m6c1 x3d h2 y5e4 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">91 </div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.000000,0.000000,0.000000,1.000000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
